akashivskyy:
I am experiencing this as well.
. Hey, I think I just found a solution. Specta "executes" the `sharedExamplesFor` block at compile-time, seeking context blocks, which are collected and executed at act-time. This means that all variables **initialized** inside the `sharedExamplesFor` are in fact initialized during compile-time.

You should read from `NSDictionary *data` inside your **`it`** blocks, instead of the root `sharedExamplesFor` block:

``` objc
// incorrect
sharedExamplesFor(@"foo", ^(NSDictionary *data) {
    id bar = data[@"bar"];
    it(@"should not be nil", ^{
        expect(bar).toNot.beNil();
    });
});

// correct
sharedExamplesFor(@"foo", ^(NSDictionary *data) {
    it(@"should not be nil", ^{
        id bar = data[@"bar"];
        expect(bar).toNot.beNil();
    });
});

// even more correct
sharedExamplesFor(@"foo", ^(NSDictionary *data) {
    __block id bar = nil;
    beforeEach(^{
        bar = data[@"bar"];
    });
    it(@"should not be nil", ^{
        expect(bar).toNot.beNil();
    });
});
```

//cc @NSDex @hatunike 
